{
  "texts": [
    "Due to the absence of anomalies, artificial anomalies for contaminated training data are generated by adding zero-mean Gaussian noise to test anomalies, as in Shenkar and Wolf [54] and Qiu et al. [21].",
    "The standard deviations for the contamination are derived from test anomalies.",
    "We measure the average AUROC with ten different seeds on each dataset.",
    "Additionally, we leverage a Gaussian mixture model with two components and set E, z, and t s as 15, 2.5, and 0.1, respectively.",
    "Comparison MethodsWe use three distinct baseline models to ensure broad applicability."
  ]
}